## Template parts
Building template parts is one of the strongest concepts of the Business Designer web application. They allow the reusability of simple components within a document. There is a difference between local template parts which can only be reused within the respective template and template part collections whose template parts can be included in any template.

## Create template parts
To create and manage template parts, use the "Template Parts" icon in the upper right corner.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Newly created documents do not yet contain any template parts. With the plus icon next to *template parts (Local) *you can create a new block.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

Fill the template part with any content by dragging the desired elements into the template part. If the template part should contain more than one text element, first drag a block or container into it, then insert the necessary elements into this element.

> Note

*Attention! If you simply enter text into the template part, only this text element will be available and it will no longer be possible to insert a block or container.*

Any number of template parts can be created in each document. Each template part must have a unique name.

As soon as the new template part is created, four options are available when clicking or mousing over the template part name.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

- Pen icon: replace the default name of the template part with an own name. Make sure that the template part names are unique.

- Magnifier/chain: shows all occurrences of the template part in the template.

- Trash icon: Delete block.

- Gear icon: Set template part parameters.

Parameters are used when the user should be able to enter situation related data when using the template (e.g. number of persons for a travel offer), i.e. you create input fields for the Workplace. As soon as you create a parameter (plus symbol in the lower left corner) an input request will appear when using the template.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

If you want to swap parts of an already existing template into a template part, you can insert the content from the template into the template part using Copy   Paste.

## Use template part
Use the editor icon to switch back to the template. On the right side of the palette, under the menu item *Template Part References*, the newly created template parts are available as icons. You can drag them into the template - or into the outline.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

> Note

*Inline-template parts can only be inserted into one block, block-level-blocks only between blocks.*

Template parts are always dynamic: The inserted template part element is not a copy of its contents but a reference, i.e. a reference to the template part. (If the template part is changed, all occurrences of the template part in the template will change). Template parts are often used to standardize parts of documents, for example the header area.

The inserted template part reference shows the template part name and whether it is a local or external template part.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

Options of the context menu:

- By clicking the "i" icon, you can quickly switch to the template part itself, e.g. if you find errors in the content. This opens the template part collection for external template parts (see below).

- Use the trashcan icon to delete the template part reference (you can also select and delete it in the outline like any other element).

- Input data for the existing parameters in the template part can be defined via settings icon (see above). The name is displayed when the template is used as an input request. The type determines the type of data that can be entered (e.g. "integer" allows only integer numbers to be entered).

If a template part that is still referenced in the template is deleted, this reference can no longer be resolved. A red bar will be displayed instead of the template part .

![](data:image/png;base64,)

## Template part package
Mostly you want to use template parts in several templates. This is possible if you create them in a template part package.

Create a package file of the type "Template Part Package".

![](data:image/png;base64,)

This package is a normal ITX file, but the template parts you create here can be referenced in template files. The package can contain any number of template parts and it can be referenced from any number of templates. Doxee recommends the use of template parts as they facilitate maintainability and reusability of template content.

You can create and manage the template parts in the template part package the same way as in a normal template file. Create as many template parts as you like in the category "Template Parts (Local)".

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

## Use the template part package - external template parts
There are two possible ways to include template parts from the package in a template:

- Include individual template parts: Use the button *Template Part Reference *on the right side of the editor view in your template under *Template Part References*: drag the button to the desired position in the template.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

This will open a file selection window. Find the template part package file. By clicking the arrow icon next to the file name you can display all containing template parts. Select the desired template part and import it.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

- Include package: Go to the template part view and use the *Add external Resource *button in the *Template Parts (External) *category. Select the package file and import it.

All the imported template parts of the package are displayed in the editor view on the right under *Template Part References *and they can be inserted in a convenient way.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

References to template parts from the package display with "EXTERNAL" after the template part name.

Even with external template part references, you can switch to the template part via the "i" icon - it will open the file in which the template part is located.

> Note

*To avoid conflicts with other importable elements from templates, external template parts should only be inserted from template part packages.*

*If you use both external and local template parts, make sure that there are no identical names. If you still have to use template parts with identical names, the deepest external template part will be rendered.*

## Sorting local template parts
Local template parts can be sorted in the template part view in the outline. The template part can be placed at the desired position in the outline by drag &amp; drop. The sorting is saved in the ItX file and displayed accordingly when reopened. Template parts that are often edited can thus be placed at the first position on top section of this view.

## Insertion Points
This element can be used to define which optional or preselected template parts are available for interactive letter writing in the *Composer*.

The element can be found in the palette under *template parts *and, like the other elements, it can be placed in the editor and outline by using drag &amp; drop.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

By placing the insertion point element, the following dialog will open:

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

In this dialog, all available template parts (local and external) are listed on the left. By clicking on the folder icon, new external template part packages can be added. The name of the insertion point and the maximum number of insertable blocks that can be inserted can be defined in the lower area of this dialog.

Local template parts can be defined individually as *available template parts *by double- clicking or by selecting the template part and clicking the arrow in the middle. External template parts can be selected and added individually or as a complete package. The available template parts or template part packages are available to the user as a selection in the composer. By clicking on the *Chosen *checkbox, the template parts can be preselected and thus inserted in advance.

In the following example, a local template part (Local-TemplatePart-1) and the external template part package (Insertionpoint_external.itx) containing the two template parts are selected as available template parts. The *Chosen *checkbox was activated for the local template part so it is preselected.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Template parts with an active *Chosen *checkbox are visualized in the editor in the insertion point element.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

If the insertion point is marked in the editor, the following attributes can be edited in the right area under *Style &amp; Properties *in the *Miscellaneous *section:

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

***allow-repeats***: determines if the same template part may be inserted more than once.

***insertion-point-description***: Brief description of the insertion point.

***insertion-point-id***: may hold a unique ID; If this is empty, Composer will generate its own ID during runtime. It is recommended to leave the insertion-point-id empty and allow Composer to generate its own unique ID. If you specify a static ID, and the Insertion Point is repeated (as part of a repeat or a template part), the ID is no longer unique and the Insertion Point cannot be used properly in Composer.

***insertion-point-name***: defines the name of the insertion point.

***max-count***: determines the total number of template parts which may be inserted by the user (the allowed range of values is 0 to unbounded)

> Note

*The selected template parts can be given parameters as well as normal template part references (see *[*Create template parts*](/doxee-platform/docs/6-6-business-designer-user-guide-create-and-use-template-parts-1#create-template-parts)*)*
